## esp haute
Horseshoe bats, which often hang upside down in caves and grottos, emit high-frequency constant frequency (CF) signals (> 80 kHz for the most "audible" harmonic). In heterodyne, their sonar signals are very fast and sharp. Here is an example for the [Lesser horseshoe bat](https://youtube.com/shorts/XgmC_SgB77o) that emits between 15 and 120 kHz:
[![Lesser horseshoe bat heterodyne](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExd3g2N3duc2dhMHg1OHloOW15NG96bGdtM3NjcnJzNW04NXRuNzB5MyZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/Qyktulx4HtdOQ89CLw/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/XgmC_SgB77o) _Guillaume Marchais_
In time expansion (x10), the sounds are even sharper:
[![Lesser horseshoe bat expansion](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExbG0zYnowOTFpeGxiNzFubThvMHFvdndodXM5YTBtb3ZsYWZneHZzbyZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/4Ref4RmsSoar6ASZBB/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/vgahZM7Np5Y) _Guillaume Marchais_
Their "big brother," the [Greater horseshoe bat](https://youtube.com/shorts/yqe4rqG5m2M) emits similar ultrasonic signals at a lower frequency:
[![Greater horseshoe bat expansion](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExbTFrc2NnbjVlcWU5ZzV1NGRoeXZwOXlrdGk5bWo3Nmx0N3M1bmk3eCZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/aGnJDGVuknjzaOhHmr/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/yqe4rqG5m2M) _Guillaume Marchais_

