## esp basse
- noctule
- nyctalus
- low frequencies
The larger species are known to emit at lower frequencies for their "sonar" sounds, typically between 8 and 25 kHz (Cestoni's bat and noctules).
In heterodyne, their sounds are rather low-pitched and widely spaced because they often fly at heights above 30 m and over long distances (tens of kilometers).
[![Noctule hunting](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExemwxajF0MHB2M3h3eXRkZGIwNGFnN3R5aDBpMjhjZWZmaTI1M3ZjciZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/7L0SnBtFm5Rz4vjXqZ/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/IbPkGTADIeQ) _Guillaume Marchais (Echo Meter Touch 2)_

In the following example, you can clearly see the difference between two species: the smaller one (Common pipistrelle) emits at higher frequencies than the larger one (Noctule commune):
[![Common pipistrelle and Common noctule bats](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExMjd6cTMwZHVxM2d5a2I2NDRybzNqZmdlNjFkcHNnY3c4azdwdHRlZCZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/I3TpZLlEyQftdbharU/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/o716J1PAqY4) _Guillaume Marchais (Echo Meter Touch 2)_

