## détecteurs
- detectors
- microphone
- microphones
- device
There are numerous devices that use one or more active or passive technologies. Active devices are used for self-prospecting, while passive devices are placed for one or more nights. Most are standalone, while others can be connected to a smartphone with a dedicated app.
A comparison of active detectors has been compiled over the years by French expert [Michel Barataud](http://ecologieacoustique.fr/wp-content/uploads/Comparatif_detecteurs-manuels_MB.pdf).
For passive detectors, there are models like the Audiomoth from Openacoustic, SMbat from Wildlife Acoustics, and Anabat from Titley scientific.
They are available from French specialized suppliers such as [Biotope](https://leclub-biotope.com/fr/124-materiel-de-terrain-logiciels), [Wildcare](https://www.wildcare.eu/chauves-souris/detecteurs-portatifs.html), and [Jama](https://www.jama.fr/boutique/fr/prise-de-son/detecteurs-chauves-souris/batbox-60).
Alternatively, an associative initiative offers the production of detectors from components in a self-managed collective. The approach is for an informed audience, as it requires delving into detailed documentation [here](https://framagit.org/PiBatRecorderPojects/TeensyRecorders) and spending some time on it... but the reward is at the end with high-quality detectors at a low cost (around 100 € per unit compared to 500 to 1500 € for those directly marketed).

