## esp rare
- rare species
* The [Myotis species](https://youtube.com/shorts/ZcZIt625iJ4) are a group of species that emit so-called frequency-modulated abrupt sounds, as the frequency drops rapidly in just a few milliseconds.
[![Murins](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExc3Jyeng0Y2xyaTR2OWdvZDk2dDNsMXdhcHFqbmpyZG84ZWpsdXc3biZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/BG7cIvh33KDA97BUvf/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/ZcZIt625iJ4) _Guillaume Marchais (Echo Meter Touch 2)_
* The [Plecotus species](https://youtu.be/PJG16JBDlVA?si=zPHDFKLZ1Pya7s0K) are species with large ears relative to their body size and tend to emit ultrasounds through their nose. They are more discreet and therefore detected less frequently.
[![Oreillards](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExcTY1cGEzODdzd2llanlxNHF3ZmtobmJtZTUwMm16NWw5aGQ2eDhsbSZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/tLHH89M4sa00cytoPA/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/uO6JgctaViE) _Guillaume Marchais (Echo Meter Touch 2)_
The Barbastelle is another discreet species that [prefers hunting nocturnal moths from the Tympanidae family](http://ecologieacoustique.fr/wp-content/uploads/Barataud_2011_Adaptation-sonar-B.barbastellus_capture-papillons.pdf) by jamming the "sonic trails" with an alternation of signals between 35 KhZ and 43 kHz approximately.
[![Barbastelle](https://media.giphy.com/media/v1.Y2lkPTc5MGI3NjExd2Zndmh4ZmYybGkycHo1aTFibzI4b3o0aW90aWl4MDJjdWphNXJtdSZlcD12MV9pbnRlcm5hbF9naWZfYnlfaWQmY3Q9Zw/fU5k7LCUBUBs9Y3ptM/giphy.gif)](https://youtube.com/shorts/eA_8P5fo5NI) _Guillaume Marchais (Echo Meter Touch 2)_
* This [dedicated search engine](https://eyssette.forge.aeif.fr/cse/#https://github.com/guillaumarchais/SearX/blob/main/chirossons) can also help you find examples of sounds visible on spectrograms. (Click on the image search once on the results page. Entering scientific names will yield more examples from English-language sources).

